>Let me cut right through here to the core of SOME of the disagreements about
>Clipper. I consider it to be MY government, and I trust it a la Mark Twain's
>"Trust everybody and always cut the cards." Thus I take at face value the
>government's implied statement that alternatives known publicly aren't
>secure and clipper is. Others may disagree, or at least raise questions, as
>is their right.
>
>Given my assumptions, the problem becomes preventing the bad guys from
>getting really secure communications. Hence the secrecy of the algorithm,
>the protection of the chip, and the key escrow with court order.
>
>It seems to me the government is trying to go pretty far in giving us the
>NSA's better stuff, and riding on my assumptions, I'll take it. You don't
